  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Restoring the Consumption of Native Foods in El Alto La Paz.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The population of El Alto in La Paz, Bolivia, largely consists of families who have migrated from the Bolivian highlands. As part of the rural to urban migration process, these families often exchange their healthy, traditional diets of Andean crops for poor quality, highly-processed and carbohydrate-rich foods, resulting in the high rates of both malnutrition and obesity among the urban poor. Other effects of poor nutrition are low energy levels and learning difficulties in school-age children, often leading to high rates of dropout. Because schoolchildren are receptive to learning and changing their habits this project will target children and also work with teachers, school boards, and parents as well as municipal authorities.
Participants include 864 families from eight educational communities , which will stimulate responsible consumption of healthy, locally produced foods. Information campaigns and training events will promote food security and the right to adequate nourishment at the family level. Another estimated 864 families from the same communities will benefit from passing on the gift of knowledge and improved food security practices aimed at improving family nutrition.</narrative>
  </description>
